english:
  title: Record on the Hall of Hidden Dwelling
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My student Song Mun-gwi changed his given name from Gwi to Jung, taking the character for "middle" or "balance." His courtesy name is Il-chang. Drawing from the character for rammed earth in "rammed earth labor," he named his dwelling the "Hall of Hidden Dwelling" and asked me to write this record.

    He spoke thus: "When I was young, my parents loved me deeply. In their deep love, they wished my body to gain prominence in the world—this much is clear. There are three paths to prominence: through Confucian learning, through office, through martial prowess. Since my nature tends toward Confucian learning, my parents named me Mun-gwi, the "culturally distinguished." Alas, how could I not meditate deeply upon such parental affection?

    "I have come to understand that each person possesses something of great value—what is called the Mandate of Heaven. When one cultivates the Mandate of Heaven and human position follows, this is what the gentleman greatly desires. Yet to seek only human position while neglecting the Mandate of Heaven is not the way of we scholars. The Mandate of Heaven consists of humaneness, righteousness, loyalty, trustworthiness, and the tireless love of goodness. These virtues are unified in one principle: balance. Therefore I have changed my name to Jung. Balance is that by which Heaven, Earth, and humanity establish themselves. Its worth knows no comparison. Thus my parents' naming carries no contradiction, and I have found a foundation for my life's endeavor. I do not merely admire some ancient sage. I wished to record this as well."

    I replied: "The meaning of balance is fully explained in the Doctrine of the Mean. Why add more words? Yet since Il-chang has named himself by the character for balance, and his dwelling the Hall of Hidden Dwelling, I recognize him as one of true aspiration. The application of balance manifests in speech and silence, in advance and retreat. Its essence is lofty, beyond imitation. Thus he built his dwelling simply, its rooms austere—here dwells Il-chang's balance.

    "Thatched roof and earthen steps: this is how the sages applied balance. Jade towers and jeweled halls: this is how later generations lost it. I admire Il-chang's way ever more.

    "Today's gentlemen, achieving their ambitions, make their dwellings magnificent, their tables abundant, satisfying desire within and displaying glory without—yet always hunger for more. Some fortunate enough to pass these to sons, and sons to grandsons, are few indeed. Some change residence before the seat grows warm, change owners before the walls dry. The Hall of Hidden Dwelling is clearly not of this kind.

    "Whether its windows are broken crockery, whether rope serves as door hinges, whether thorns form its gate, whether it resembles a cave or earthen hovel, whether rain leaks through its roof and wind enters its sides—of this I cannot speak with certainty. Yet one thing is sure: conversation within will include the realm's finest scholars, and visitors will include none of common name. Il-chang dwelling in such peace must surely harbor aspiration. Is this not the spirit of Fu Yüeh in the wilds of Fu Rock? Whether the High King dreams—this rests with Heaven.

    "If Il-chang but grasps the way of balance firmly, to end his days in the Hall of Hidden Dwelling need not be lamented, nor would sketching its form and seeking it throughout the world be unwelcome. Does balance reside in people or in Heaven? The good receive blessing, the chaotic receive calamity—the pattern is manifest. Heaven's way errs not of itself. Let Il-chang redouble his effort."
  footnotes:
    - Fu Yüeh was a sage discovered by the High King while laboring in the wilds of Fu Rock, symbolizing hidden virtue recognized by Heaven.
    - The Doctrine of the Mean (中庸) is a Confucian classic emphasizing balance and harmony as the foundation of moral cultivation.
    - '"Rammed earth labor" refers to common laborers, suggesting humility and simplicity in dwelling.'
    - The Hall of Hidden Dwelling represents withdrawal from worldly ambition to cultivate inner virtue—a traditional ideal in East Asian literati culture.
